2. RQ2 (Plasticity Rules and Dynamic Routing): How do different mathematical formulations of plasticity (Hebbian, covariance, BCM, STDP) interact with dynamic routing by agreement? Can we prove that a two‑timescale update scheme (fast routing, slow plasticity) converges and tracks the optimal coupling coefficients despite continuous weight changes?
3. RQ3 (Multi‑Nuclei Emergence and Hamiltonian Stability): Can multiple nuclei, each governing a subset of capsules, coordinate via inter‑nuclei highways to exhibit emergent problem‑solving behaviours not present in a single‑nucleus system? How can the system be formalised as a port‑Hamiltonian dynamical system with passivity‑based control, and under what conditions can we prove asymptotic stability to an equilibrium set, even under structural adaptation (generation/pruning of capsules)?
4. RQ4 (Causal Emergence and Distributed Intelligence): What quantitative metrics can capture the degree of distributed intelligence in a multi‑nuclei system? Can Causal Emergence 2.0 primitives (determinism, specificity) be apportioned across hierarchical scales (capsules → nuclei → inter‑nuclei) to compute emergent complexity \mathcal{E} and a distributed intelligence metric \mathcal{D}, and can these be shown to be consistent estimators under mild ergodicity assumptions?
