Chapter 2: Mathematical Preliminaries and Related Frameworks

This chapter collects the mathematical concepts and existing frameworks that form the foundation of the thesis. No empirical results are discussed; only the essential definitions and known theorems are stated.

2.1 Neural Plasticity as Dynamical Systems

Let a neuron be characterised by an activity variable x \in \mathbb{R}. A synapse from pre‑synaptic neuron i to post‑synaptic neuron j has weight w_{ij} \in \mathbb{R}.

Definition 2.1 (Hebbian Rule).

\frac{d w_{ij}}{dt} = \eta \, x_i x_j - \gamma w_{ij},

with learning rate \eta>0 and decay \gamma>0. The fixed point satisfies w_{ij}^* = \frac{\eta}{\gamma} x_i x_j.

Definition 2.2 (Covariance Rule).
Let \langle x_i \rangle be a running average. Then

\frac{d w_{ij}}{dt} = \eta (x_i - \langle x_i \rangle)(x_j - \langle x_j \rangle).

Definition 2.3 (BCM Rule).

\frac{d w_{ij}}{dt} = \eta \, x_i x_j (x_j - \theta_j), \qquad
\frac{d\theta_j}{dt} = \frac{1}{\tau}(x_j^2 - \theta_j).

The sliding threshold \theta_j provides homeostatic stability.

Definition 2.4 (STDP – trace model).
Define traces \mathrm{tr}_{\text{pre}}(t), \mathrm{tr}_{\text{post}}(t) by

\frac{d\mathrm{tr}}{dt} = -\frac{\mathrm{tr}}{\tau} + x(t).

Then

\Delta w_{ij} = A_+ \, \mathrm{tr}_{\text{pre}} \, x_{\text{post}} - A_- \, \mathrm{tr}_{\text{post}} \, x_{\text{pre}}.

Theorem 2.1 (BCM Stability – known result).
Under the BCM rule, the average synaptic weight remains bounded and the neuron becomes selective to inputs that consistently exceed the threshold. (Proof follows from Lyapunov function \frac{1}{2}\sum_i w_{ij}^2 + \frac{1}{2}\theta_j^2.)

2.2 Evolving Neural Networks as Topological Dynamical Systems

A neural network is a directed graph G = (V,E). NEAT (NeuroEvolution of Augmenting Topologies) evolves both weights and structure via crossover and mutation. The key mathematical object is the genotype–phenotype map. For our purposes, we abstract the process as a discrete‑time dynamical system on the space of graphs.

Definition 2.5 (Graph Evolution Operator).
Let \mathcal{G} be the set of all finite directed graphs with real‑valued edge weights. An evolution operator \mathcal{E}: \mathcal{G} \to \mathcal{G} adds or removes nodes and edges according to a probability distribution that may depend on fitness.

Lemma 2.1 (NEAT Complexification).
Under the NEAT mutation operator, the expected number of nodes and edges grows at most exponentially with generations. (Proof by branching process bound.)

2.3 Capsule Networks and Dynamic Routing

Definition 2.6 (Capsule).
A capsule c outputs a vector \mathbf{u}_c \in \mathbb{R}^d obtained by

\mathbf{s}_c = \mathbf{W}_c \mathbf{x}, \qquad \mathbf{u}_c = \mathrm{squash}(\mathbf{s}_c),

where \mathbf{W}_c \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times n} and \mathrm{squash}(\mathbf{s}) = \frac{\|\mathbf{s}\|^2}{1+\|\mathbf{s}\|^2}\frac{\mathbf{s}}{\|\mathbf{s}\|}.

Definition 2.7 (Dynamic Routing).
For a lower‑level capsule i and higher‑level capsule j, the prediction vector is \hat{\mathbf{u}}_{j|i} = \mathbf{W}_{ij}\mathbf{u}_i. Let b_{ij} be logits. Routing iterates:

c_{ij} = \frac{\exp(b_{ij})}{\sum_k \exp(b_{ik})},\quad
\mathbf{s}_j = \sum_i c_{ij}\hat{\mathbf{u}}_{j|i},\quad
\mathbf{v}_j = \mathrm{squash}(\mathbf{s}_j),\quad
b_{ij} \leftarrow b_{ij} + \mathbf{v}_j\cdot\hat{\mathbf{u}}_{j|i}.

Theorem 2.2 (Convergence of Dynamic Routing – known).
The algorithm converges to a fixed point (\mathbf{c}^*, \mathbf{v}^*) that is a stationary point of the concave objective

\mathcal{L}(\mathbf{c}) = \sum_j \|\mathbf{v}_j\|^2 - \frac12\sum_{i,j} c_{ij}^2\|\hat{\mathbf{u}}_{j|i}\|^2,

subject to \sum_j c_{ij}=1. The convergence is geometric.

2.4 Port‑Hamiltonian Systems

Definition 2.8 (Port‑Hamiltonian System).
Let \mathbf{x} \in \mathbb{R}^n be the state, H(\mathbf{x}) the Hamiltonian (storage function). The dynamics are

\dot{\mathbf{x}} = (\mathbf{J}(\mathbf{x}) - \mathbf{R}(\mathbf{x}))\nabla H(\mathbf{x}) + \mathbf{g}(\mathbf{x})\mathbf{u},

with \mathbf{J}^\top = -\mathbf{J} (interconnection), \mathbf{R} \succeq 0 (damping), \mathbf{u} the input, \mathbf{g} the input matrix.

Theorem 2.3 (Passivity).
With output \mathbf{y} = \mathbf{g}(\mathbf{x})^\top \nabla H(\mathbf{x}), the system satisfies \dot{H} \le \mathbf{u}^\top \mathbf{y}. For \mathbf{u}=0, H is non‑increasing.

2.5 Causal Emergence 2.0

Definition 2.9 (Transition Probability Matrix).
For a discrete‑state Markov chain with n states, let T \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times n} with T_{ij} = \Pr(s_{t+1}=j \mid s_t=i).

Definition 2.10 (Determinism, Specificity, Causal Power).

\mathrm{det}(T) = 1 - \frac1n\sum_i H(T_{i\cdot}),\quad
\mathrm{spec}(T) = 1 - \frac1n\sum_j H(T_{\cdot j}),

\mathrm{CP}(T) = \mathrm{det}(T) + \mathrm{spec}(T) - 1,

where H is Shannon entropy.

Theorem 2.4 (Consistency of CP Estimation – known).
Given N i.i.d. samples from an ergodic chain, the plug‑in estimator \widehat{\mathrm{CP}} satisfies |\widehat{\mathrm{CP}} - \mathrm{CP}| = O_p(\sqrt{\log n / (N\pi_{\min})}).

2.6 Gaps in the Literature

No existing work combines:

· Online structural plasticity with vector capsules and dynamic routing.
· Hamiltonian stability proofs under topology changes.
· Causal Emergence 2.0 applied to self‑generating hierarchies.
· A formal theorem on epistemic blind spots and their compression via meta‑expansion.

