Chapter 5: Multi‑Nuclei Hamiltonian System and Stability

This chapter extends the single‑nucleus port‑Hamiltonian formulation to multiple interacting nuclei. We prove passivity, asymptotic stability for fixed topologies, and then analyse the effect of structural adaptation (capsule/highway generation and pruning) under the bounded growth guarantees of Lemma 4.1. All results are purely analytical.

5.1 Smooth Squashing for Analytical Tractability

For theoretical proofs, we replace the original squashing function with a smooth, globally Lipschitz surrogate.

Definition 5.1 (Smooth Squashing).
For \mathbf{s} \in \mathbb{R}^d,

\tilde{f}(\mathbf{s}) = \begin{cases}
\tanh(\|\mathbf{s}\|)\,\dfrac{\mathbf{s}}{\|\mathbf{s}\|}, & \mathbf{s} \neq \mathbf{0},\\[6pt]
\mathbf{0}, & \mathbf{s} = \mathbf{0}.
\end{cases}

Lemma 5.1 (Lipschitz Continuity).
\tilde{f} is globally Lipschitz with constant L=1.

Proof. For \mathbf{s}_1, \mathbf{s}_2 \neq \mathbf{0},

\|\tilde{f}(\mathbf{s}_1)-\tilde{f}(\mathbf{s}_2)\|
\le \|\tanh(\|\mathbf{s}_1\|)-\tanh(\|\mathbf{s}_2\|)\|
+ \tanh(\|\mathbf{s}_2\|)\left\|\frac{\mathbf{s}_1}{\|\mathbf{s}_1\|}-\frac{\mathbf{s}_2}{\|\mathbf{s}_2\|}\right\|.

Since \tanh is 1-Lipschitz and the unit vector map is non‑expansive, the right‑hand side is bounded by \|\mathbf{s}_1-\mathbf{s}_2\|. The case where one argument is zero follows by continuity. ∎

In the sequel, we assume all capsule outputs are computed using \tilde{f}; the original squashing can be seen as an approximation with identical fixed‑point properties.

5.2 Port‑Hamiltonian Dynamics with Self‑Attention Damping

We consider a system of K nuclei. Let the global state be \mathbf{x} = [\mathbf{q}^\top, \mathbf{p}^\top]^\top \in \mathbb{R}^{2N}, where N is the total number of capsules across all nuclei. The vector \mathbf{q} collects capsule outputs, and \mathbf{p} collects conjugate momenta (auxiliary internal states).

Definition 5.2 (Hamiltonian).

H(\mathbf{q},\mathbf{p}) = \underbrace{\sum_{i=1}^{N} \frac{1}{2}\|\mathbf{p}_i\|^2}_{\text{kinetic}} \;+\; \underbrace{\sum_{i=1}^{N} V_i(\mathbf{q}_i)}_{\text{internal potential}} \;+\; \underbrace{\sum_{(i,j)\in E} \Phi_{ij}(\mathbf{q}_i,\mathbf{q}_j)}_{\text{interaction potential}}.

Here V_i is derived from the capsule’s activation function (e.g., V_i(\mathbf{q}_i) = -\log(1-\|\mathbf{q}_i\|^2) after squashing), and \Phi_{ij}(\mathbf{q}_i,\mathbf{q}_j) = -\mathbf{q}_j\cdot (\mathbf{W}_{ij}\mathbf{q}_i) captures the agreement energy. All potentials are assumed twice continuously differentiable.

Definition 5.3 (Self‑Attention Parameterisation).
Let \mathbf{J}(\mathbf{x}) be skew‑symmetric and \mathbf{R}(\mathbf{x}) symmetric positive semidefinite, both parameterised by multi‑head self‑attention over the set of capsules:

\mathbf{J}(\mathbf{x}) = \mathrm{Attn}(\mathbf{x}) - \mathrm{Attn}(\mathbf{x})^\top, \qquad
\mathbf{R}(\mathbf{x}) = \mathrm{Softplus}\bigl(\mathrm{Attn}(\mathbf{x})\bigr),

where \mathrm{Attn}(\mathbf{x}) is the attention matrix computed from \mathbf{x} (e.g., via \mathrm{softmax}(\mathbf{x}\mathbf{x}^\top/\sqrt{d})). This ensures \mathbf{J} is skew‑symmetric and \mathbf{R} positive definite in practice (strictly positive diagonal after Softplus).

Definition 5.4 (Port‑Hamiltonian Dynamics).
For \mathbf{u}=0 (no external input after initial training),

\dot{\mathbf{x}} = \bigl(\mathbf{J}(\mathbf{x}) - \mathbf{R}(\mathbf{x})\bigr)\nabla H(\mathbf{x}).

Theorem 5.1 (Passivity and Energy Dissipation).
The Hamiltonian H satisfies

\dot{H} = -\nabla H(\mathbf{x})^\top \mathbf{R}(\mathbf{x}) \nabla H(\mathbf{x}) \le 0.

Proof. Differentiating along trajectories,

\dot{H} = \nabla H^\top \dot{\mathbf{x}} = \nabla H^\top (\mathbf{J} - \mathbf{R})\nabla H = \nabla H^\top \mathbf{J}\nabla H - \nabla H^\top \mathbf{R}\nabla H.

Since \mathbf{J} is skew‑symmetric, \nabla H^\top \mathbf{J}\nabla H = 0. Because \mathbf{R} \succeq 0, the quadratic form is non‑positive. Hence \dot{H} \le 0. ∎

Corollary 5.1 (Boundedness).
For all t\ge 0, H(t) \le H(0) and H(t) is bounded below (by construction, H \ge 0). Therefore H(t) converges to a finite limit as t\to\infty.

Theorem 5.2 (Asymptotic Stability for Fixed Topology).
Assume the set \mathcal{E} = \{\mathbf{x} : \nabla H(\mathbf{x})^\top \mathbf{R}(\mathbf{x})\nabla H(\mathbf{x}) = 0\} contains no complete trajectories other than equilibria. Then every trajectory converges to an equilibrium as t\to\infty.

Proof. H is a non‑increasing Lyapunov function bounded below. By LaSalle’s invariance principle, the trajectory approaches the largest invariant set contained in \mathcal{E}. By hypothesis, that set consists only of equilibria. Hence \mathbf{x}(t) \to \mathbf{x}^* with \nabla H(\mathbf{x}^*)=0 (or \mathbf{R}(\mathbf{x}^*)\nabla H(\mathbf{x}^*)=0 which, if \mathbf{R} is positive definite on the tangent space, implies \nabla H=0). ∎

5.3 Stability Under Structural Adaptation

Structural changes (capsule/highway generation or pruning) occur at discrete times t_1, t_2, \dots. Between events, the topology is fixed and Theorem 5.2 applies. At an event, the Hamiltonian may jump because new terms appear or disappear. We analyse the effect.

Assumption 5.1 (Lipschitz Attention).
The attention modules that define \mathbf{J} and \mathbf{R} are Lipschitz continuous with respect to the network parameters (weights, capsule outputs). When a capsule is added or removed, the parameter change \delta_{\text{params}} satisfies \|\mathbf{J}' - \mathbf{J}\| \le L_{\text{att}}\delta_{\text{params}} and similarly for \mathbf{R}.

Assumption 5.2 (Bounded New Terms).
For any new capsule c, the potential V_c(\mathbf{q}_c) is bounded (since \|\mathbf{q}_c\|\le 1 by squashing). For any new highway (i,j), the interaction potential \Phi_{ij} is bounded (because the agreement \mathbf{v}_j\cdot\hat{\mathbf{u}}_{j|i} lies in [-1,1]). Removal of capsules/highways removes bounded terms.

Proposition 5.1 (Bounded Energy Jumps).
At a structural change event, the Hamiltonian changes by at most a constant C>0 that depends only on the number of added/removed elements and the bounds on potentials.

Proof. Let H_- be the Hamiltonian just before the event, H_+ just after. The difference H_+ - H_- is the sum of potentials of added capsules and highways minus those of removed ones. Each such term is bounded in absolute value by a constant (e.g., \max \|\mathbf{q}\|^2/2 for kinetic, \max V_i for internal, and \max |\Phi_{ij}| for interactions). Hence |H_+ - H_-| \le C with C = n_{\text{add}}\cdot B_{\text{max}} + n_{\text{remove}}\cdot B_{\text{max}}. ∎

Lemma 5.2 (Finiteness of Structural Events).
Under the hybrid generation trigger (Definition 3.7) and homeostatic scaling, the total number of insertions and prunings is almost surely finite. (Proof follows from Lemma 4.1, as the expected number of insertions is bounded and pruning only removes silent capsules, which cannot be re‑inserted infinitely often.)

Theorem 5.3 (Convergence Under Structural Adaptation).
Assume the system undergoes a finite sequence of structural changes at times t_1 < t_2 < \dots < t_M. Between changes, the dynamics satisfy \dot{H} \le 0. At each change, the Hamiltonian jumps by at most C. Then H(t) converges to a finite limit as t\to\infty, and the state converges to a neighbourhood of an equilibrium set.

Proof. Consider the sequence H(t_1^-), H(t_1^+), H(t_2^-), H(t_2^+), \dots. Between events, H is non‑increasing and bounded below, so each interval limit exists. The total upward jump is at most M C. Hence the overall sequence H(t) is a piecewise monotone function with bounded total variation, therefore convergent to some H_\infty. Because after the last event the system is fixed‑topology and satisfies Theorem 5.2, the trajectory converges to an equilibrium of that final system. The convergence is asymptotic; the transient due to jumps does not prevent convergence to a neighbourhood (in fact, to the exact equilibrium because the final dynamics are dissipative). ∎

Corollary 5.2 (Residual Blind Spot and Stability).
Even after structural adaptation stops, the final hypothesis space \mathcal{H}_T may still have a positive blind spot measure \mu(\mathcal{B}_T) > 0. The Hamiltonian stability guarantees that the system will converge to an equilibrium within its representable states, but it cannot “know” about the blind spot. This aligns with the Blind Spot Theorem (Section 3.0): stability does not imply completeness.

