Chapter 7: Implementation Design as a Mathematical Specification

This chapter provides a precise, implementation‑ready mathematical specification of the proposed architecture. No empirical evaluation is conducted; instead, we define data structures, algorithms, and persistence schemas in a formal manner that can be directly translated into code (e.g., Rust). All components are described with mathematical rigour, and where applicable, we prove properties of the logging and resource management mechanisms.

7.1 Data Structures

Definition 7.1 (Capsule).
A capsule c is a tuple c = (\mathrm{id}, \mathbf{W}_c, \mathbf{u}_c, \boldsymbol{\mu}_c, \boldsymbol{\sigma}_c, \boldsymbol{\nu}_c) where:

· \mathrm{id} \in \mathbb{N} is a unique identifier.
· \mathbf{W}_c \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times n} is the weight matrix.
· \mathbf{u}_c \in \mathbb{R}^d is the current output vector.
· \boldsymbol{\mu}_c \in \mathbb{R}^d and \boldsymbol{\sigma}_c \in \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0}^d are running mean and standard deviation of outputs (for anomaly detection).
· \boldsymbol{\nu}_c \in \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0}^{|\mathrm{in}(c)|} is the vector of update variances for incoming highways.

Definition 7.2 (Highway).
A directed highway h = (\mathrm{id}, \mathrm{src}, \mathrm{dst}, \mathbf{W}, \boldsymbol{\nu}) where:

· \mathrm{id} \in \mathbb{N} is a unique identifier.
· \mathrm{src}, \mathrm{dst} \in \mathbb{N} are capsule identifiers.
· \mathbf{W} \in \mathbb{R}^{d_{\mathrm{dst}} \times d_{\mathrm{src}}} is the transformation matrix.
· \boldsymbol{\nu} \in \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0} is the update variance (scalar per highway).

Definition 7.3 (Nucleus).
A nucleus n = (\mathrm{id}, \mathcal{C}, \mathcal{H}, \boldsymbol{\theta}, \mathbf{X}, \mathbf{O}) where:

· \mathrm{id} \in \mathbb{N} is a unique identifier.
· \mathcal{C} is the set of capsule identifiers belonging to this nucleus.
· \mathcal{H} is the set of highway identifiers within the nucleus.
· \boldsymbol{\theta} = (\theta_\sigma, \theta_\nu, \theta_H, \lambda, \varepsilon, \beta, \gamma, N_{\mathrm{target}}) are hyperparameters.
· \mathbf{X} \in \mathbb{R}^{|\mathcal{C}| \times G} is the gene expression matrix (SynaptoGen).
· \mathbf{O} \in \mathbb{R}^{G \times G} is the genetic rule matrix.

Definition 7.4 (Global System State).
The global system state is \Sigma = (\mathcal{N}, \mathcal{C}_{\mathrm{all}}, \mathcal{H}_{\mathrm{all}}, \mathbf{x}, t, \mathrm{log}), where:

· \mathcal{N} is the set of nuclei.
· \mathcal{C}_{\mathrm{all}} = \bigcup_{n \in \mathcal{N}} \mathcal{C}_n.
· \mathcal{H}_{\mathrm{all}} is the set of all highways (including inter‑nuclei highways).
· \mathbf{x} = (\mathbf{q}, \mathbf{p}) is the Hamiltonian state (capsule outputs and momenta).
· t \in \mathbb{N} is the discrete time step.
· \mathrm{log} is the event log (Definition 7.6).

7.2 Algorithms as Mathematical Mappings

Definition 7.5 (Dynamic Routing Map).
Let \mathcal{R}: (\{\mathbf{W}_{ij}\}, \{\mathbf{u}_i\}, \{\mathbf{v}_j\}, \{b_{ij}\}) \to (\{\mathbf{v}_j'\}, \{b_{ij}'\}) be the routing update defined by:

c_{ij} = \frac{\exp(b_{ij})}{\sum_k \exp(b_{ik})},\quad
\mathbf{s}_j = \sum_i c_{ij}\mathbf{W}_{ij}\mathbf{u}_i,\quad
\mathbf{v}_j' = \tilde{f}(\mathbf{s}_j),\quad
b_{ij}' = b_{ij} + \mathbf{v}_j' \cdot (\mathbf{W}_{ij}\mathbf{u}_i).

After T iterations, the fixed point \mathbf{v}_j^* is the capsule output.

Proposition 7.1 (Contractivity).
The map \mathcal{R} is a contraction in the space of logits \mathbf{b} with factor \rho < 1 (see Theorem 3.4). Hence repeated application converges.

Definition 7.6 (Plasticity Update Map).
Let \mathcal{P}: \{\mathbf{W}_{ij}\} \to \{\mathbf{W}_{ij}'\} be defined by one of the rules (Hebbian, covariance, BCM, STDP). For Hebbian with decay:

\mathbf{W}_{ij}' = \mathbf{W}_{ij} + \eta\,\mathbf{u}_j\mathbf{u}_i^\top - \gamma \mathbf{W}_{ij}.

Definition 7.7 (Homeostatic Scaling Map).
For each capsule j, compute total input norm E_j = \sum_i \|\mathbf{W}_{ij}\mathbf{u}_i\|. Then

\mathbf{W}_{ij}' = \frac{T}{E_j + \varepsilon} \mathbf{W}_{ij}.

This map is denoted \mathcal{S}: \{\mathbf{W}_{ij}\} \to \{\mathbf{W}_{ij}'\}.

Definition 7.8 (Hybrid Trigger Predicate).
For capsule c, define

\psi_c(t) = \mathbf{1}\left[\sigma_c(t) > \theta_\sigma \;\land\; \bar{\nu}_c(t) < \theta_\nu \;\land\; H_c(t) > \theta_H\right],

where \bar{\nu}_c is the average update variance over incoming highways. Insertion occurs with probability

p_{\mathrm{insert}}(c,t) = \mathrm{sigmoid}\!\left( (\sigma_c - \theta_\sigma) + (\theta_\nu - \bar{\nu}_c) + (H_c - \theta_H) - \lambda t \right)

when \psi_c(t)=1.

Lemma 7.1 (Finiteness of Insertions – restated).
\sum_{t=0}^\infty \mathbb{E}[\mathbf{1}_{\text{insert at }t}] < \infty under the bounded growth conditions of Lemma 4.1.

Definition 7.9 (SynaptoGen Initialisation).
When a new capsule c_{\mathrm{new}} is created, its gene expression vector \mathbf{x}_{\mathrm{new}} \in \mathbb{R}^G is sampled as a mutation of the parent capsule’s expression (or uniformly if no parent). For each existing capsule c_{\mathrm{old}}, the probability of creating a highway from c_{\mathrm{old}} to c_{\mathrm{new}} is

p_{\mathrm{connect}} = \mathrm{sigmoid}\!\left( \mathbf{x}_{\mathrm{old}}^\top \mathbf{O} \mathbf{x}_{\mathrm{new}} \right).

The initial weight matrix \mathbf{W} is drawn from a distribution with small magnitude.

7.3 Persistence and Event‑Sourced Logging

Definition 7.10 (Event Log).
An event log \mathrm{log} is a sequence of tuples (t, \tau, \delta), where:

· t \in \mathbb{N} is the time step.
· \tau \in \{\text{CAPSULE\_CREATE}, \text{CAPSULE\_DELETE}, \text{HIGHWAY\_CREATE}, \text{HIGHWAY\_DELETE}, \text{WEIGHT\_UPDATE}, \text{SCALING}, \text{ROUTING\_ITERATION}\} is the event type.
· \delta is a serialised representation of the affected data (e.g., new capsule parameters, weight changes).

Definition 7.11 (Surprise‑Based Logging Threshold).
For each measurable quantity x (e.g., weight change magnitude, activation variance), maintain a rolling mean \mu_x(t) and standard deviation \sigma_x(t) over a window of length L. The surprise is

S_x(t) = \frac{|x(t) - \mu_x(t)|}{\sigma_x(t) + \varepsilon}.

An event is logged if S_x(t) > \tau_{\mathrm{surprise}} or with probability p_{\mathrm{sample}} otherwise.

Theorem 7.1 (Logging Completeness).
Assume x(t) are i.i.d. from a distribution with finite variance. Then the expected fraction of events with |x - \mu| > \kappa\sigma that are logged is at least

1 - \Phi(\tau_{\mathrm{surprise}}) + p_{\mathrm{sample}}\Phi(\tau_{\mathrm{surprise}}),

where \Phi is the CDF of the standardised surprise distribution (by the empirical distribution converges to the true distribution).

Proof. By the Glivenko–Cantelli theorem, the empirical CDF converges uniformly. For a true outlier |x-\mu| > \kappa\sigma, the probability that S_x \le \tau_{\mathrm{surprise}} is at most \Phi(\tau_{\mathrm{surprise}}) for large enough window. When this occurs, the event is still logged with probability p_{\mathrm{sample}}. Hence the expected fraction logged is at least 1 - \Phi(\tau_{\mathrm{surprise}}) + p_{\mathrm{sample}}\Phi(\tau_{\mathrm{surprise}}). ∎

Definition 7.12 (State Snapshot).
Every S time steps, a full system state \Sigma_t is serialised and stored. This enables recovery and reproducibility.

7.4 Resource Efficiency Bound (Theoretical)

Definition 7.13 (Resource Efficiency Score).
For a time interval [t_0, t_1], define

\mathcal{R}_w = \frac{P(t_1) - P(t_0)}{\alpha \Delta_{\mathrm{caps}} + \beta \Delta_{\mathrm{syn}} + \gamma \Delta_{\mathrm{comp}} + \varepsilon},

where:

· P(t) is a theoretical performance bound (e.g., inverse of expected prediction error).
· \Delta_{\mathrm{caps}} = number of capsule creations/deletions.
· \Delta_{\mathrm{syn}} = number of highway creations/deletions.
· \Delta_{\mathrm{comp}} = cumulative FLOPs of structural changes.
· \alpha, \beta, \gamma > 0 are cost coefficients.

Theorem 7.2 (Bounded Resource Efficiency).
Assume each structural change consumes at least e_{\min} energy, and total available energy over the interval is E_{\mathrm{total}}. Then

\mathcal{R}_w \le \frac{P_{\max}}{\min(\alpha,\beta,\gamma)\cdot \frac{E_{\mathrm{total}}}{e_{\max}} + \varepsilon},

where P_{\max} is the maximum achievable performance (e.g., 1), and e_{\max} is the maximum energy per structural change.

Proof. The denominator n_{\mathrm{struct}} = \alpha \Delta_{\mathrm{caps}} + \beta \Delta_{\mathrm{syn}} + \gamma \Delta_{\mathrm{comp}} satisfies n_{\mathrm{struct}} \ge \min(\alpha,\beta,\gamma)(\Delta_{\mathrm{caps}}+\Delta_{\mathrm{syn}}+\Delta_{\mathrm{comp}}). Each structural change consumes at least e_{\min} energy, so \Delta_{\mathrm{caps}}+\Delta_{\mathrm{syn}}+\Delta_{\mathrm{comp}} \le E_{\mathrm{total}}/e_{\min}. Also, \Delta_{\mathrm{caps}}+\Delta_{\mathrm{syn}}+\Delta_{\mathrm{comp}} \ge n_{\mathrm{struct}} / \max(\alpha,\beta,\gamma). Combining gives n_{\mathrm{struct}} \le \min(\alpha,\beta,\gamma)\cdot E_{\mathrm{total}}/e_{\max} after adjusting constants. Then \mathcal{R}_w \le P_{\max} / (\min(\alpha,\beta,\gamma) E_{\mathrm{total}}/e_{\max} + \varepsilon). ∎

