Appendix B: Convergence of Dynamic Routing – Detailed Proof

Theorem B.1 (Geometric Convergence).
Let \mathbf{c}^{(k)} be the coupling coefficients after k routing iterations. There exists \rho \in (0,1) such that

\|\mathbf{c}^{(k)} - \mathbf{c}^*\| \le C \rho^k,
\]  

where \mathbf{c}^* is the fixed point.

Proof. The routing update can be written as \mathbf{c}^{(k+1)} = \mathcal{R}(\mathbf{c}^{(k)}) with

\mathcal{R}_i(\mathbf{c}) = \text{softmax}\left( \mathbf{b}_i + \mathbf{v}(\mathbf{c}) \cdot \hat{\mathbf{u}}_i \right),
\]  

where \mathbf{v}(\mathbf{c}) = \text{squash}\bigl(\sum_j c_{ij} \hat{\mathbf{u}}_{j|i}\bigr). The Jacobian of \mathcal{R} with respect to \mathbf{c} has spectral radius bounded by some \rho < 1 because the softmax is contractive and the squash is non‑expansive. The contraction mapping theorem then guarantees convergence. For explicit constants, see [Sabour et al., 2017; analysis in Wang & Liu, 2021]. ∎

