Appendix C: SynaptoGen – Probabilistic Derivation

Definition C.1 (Binomial Synapse Count).
For gene pair (g,h), let X_{gh} \sim \text{Binomial}(n_{gh}, p_{gh}) with n_{gh} = x_g y_h, p_{gh} = O_{gh}. Then total expected synapses

\mathbb{E}[B] = \sum_{g,h} n_{gh} p_{gh} = \sum_{g,h} x_g y_h O_{gh} = \mathbf{x}^\top \mathbf{O} \mathbf{y}.

Proposition C.1 (Gradient).
\frac{\partial \mathbb{E}[B]}{\partial \mathbf{x}} = \mathbf{O} \mathbf{y}, \frac{\partial \mathbb{E}[B]}{\partial \mathbf{y}} = \mathbf{O}^\top \mathbf{x}, \frac{\partial \mathbb{E}[B]}{\partial \mathbf{O}} = \mathbf{x} \mathbf{y}^\top.

Proof. Direct differentiation of the bilinear form. ∎

Proposition C.2 (Conductance Extension).
For neurotransmitter distribution \mathbf{q} and receptor distribution \mathbf{r}, expected conductance \mathbb{E}[G] = \mathbf{q}^\top \mathbf{A} \mathbf{r} with \mathbf{A} the conductance matrix.

