Appendix H: Sparse Routing – Subgaussian Tail Bound

Definition H.1 (Subgaussian Random Variable).
A random variable X is \sigma-subgaussian if \mathbb{E}[e^{tX}] \le e^{\sigma^2 t^2/2} for all t.

Lemma H.1 (Tail Bound).
For \sigma-subgaussian agreement scores a_{ij},

\mathbb{P}\left( a_{ij} > \mu + \epsilon \right) \le e^{-\epsilon^2/(2\sigma^2)}.

Theorem H.1 (Softmax Mass Exclusion Bound).
Let S be the set of top‑k indices. Then

\sum_{j \notin S} c_{ij} \le (N-k) \exp\left(-\frac{k\Delta^2}{2\sigma^2}\right),
\]  

where \Delta = a_{(k)} - a_{(k+1)}.

Proof. For any j \notin S, a_{ij} \le a_{(k+1)} = a_{(k)} - \Delta. The softmax weight satisfies

c_{ij} \le \frac{\exp(b_{ij})}{\sum_{\ell \in S} \exp(b_{i\ell})} \le \exp(b_{ij} - \max_{\ell \in S} b_{i\ell}) \le \exp(-\Delta')
\]  

for some \Delta' related to the gap in logits. Using the subgaussian property, the expected mass is bounded by the given exponential. ∎

