Appendix L: Multi‑Information and Distributed Intelligence – Properties

Definition L.1 (Multi‑Information).
For K random variables X_1,\dots,X_K,

I(X_1;\dots;X_K) = \sum_{i=1}^K H(X_i) - H(X_1,\dots,X_K).

Proposition L.1 (Bounds).
0 \le I \le \sum_{i=1}^K H(X_i). The lower bound is achieved when all variables are independent; the upper bound when all are functions of a single variable.

Proposition L.2 (Monotonicity).
Adding more variables cannot decrease multi‑information: I(X_1,\dots,X_K) \le I(X_1,\dots,X_K,X_{K+1}).

Definition L.2 (Distributed Intelligence).
\mathcal{D} = \bar{\mathcal{E}} + I(N_1;\dots;N_K).

Proposition L.3 (Interpretation).
\mathcal{D} is non‑negative. It increases with both the complexity of causal hierarchy (\bar{\mathcal{E}}) and the degree of coordination among nuclei (I). Maximum \mathcal{D} occurs when causal power is evenly spread across scales and nuclei are maximally dependent.

