Appendix M: Blind Spot Theorem – Topological vs. Measure‑Theoretic Versions

Definition M.1 (Topological Blind Spot).
\mathcal{B}_{\text{top}} = W \setminus \overline{\mathcal{R}(s_0)}, where closure is taken in the topology of W.

Theorem M.1 (Topological Necessity – Conditional).
If \mathcal{H} is not dense in W, then \mathcal{B}_{\text{top}} \neq \emptyset.

Proof. If \mathcal{H} is not dense, \overline{\mathcal{H}} \subsetneq W. Since \overline{\mathcal{R}(s_0)} \subseteq \overline{\mathcal{H}}, the complement is non‑empty. ∎

Theorem M.2 (Measure‑Theoretic Necessity – Unconditional).
If \mu(\mathcal{H}) < 1, then \mu(\mathcal{B}_{\text{meas}}) > 0, where \mathcal{B}_{\text{meas}} = W \setminus \overline{\mathcal{R}(s_0)}^{\mu} (closure in measure). The proof is given in Theorem 3.1.

Example M.1 (Dense Hypothesis Space).
Let W = [0,1] with Lebesgue measure, \mathcal{H} = \mathbb{Q} \cap [0,1] (rationals). Then \mathcal{H} is dense, so \mathcal{B}_{\text{top}} = \emptyset, but \mu(\mathcal{H}) = 0 < 1, so \mu(\mathcal{B}_{\text{meas}}) = 1. The topological version fails; the measure‑theoretic version always holds when \mu(\mathcal{H}) < 1. This justifies our use of the measure‑theoretic formulation.

Corollary M.1 (Internal Undetectability – Formal).
For any measurable set U \subseteq W with U \cap \mathcal{H} = \emptyset, there is no measurable function \phi: \mathcal{H} \to \{0,1\} such that \phi(h) = 0 for all h \in \mathcal{H} and \phi(w)=1 for all w \in U. Proof by contradiction: such a \phi would imply that U is in the \sigma-algebra generated by \mathcal{H}, but U is disjoint from \mathcal{H} and not in its generated algebra because \mathcal{H} is not a basis for the whole space.

